<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,417,2028]" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,463,417,443]" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">Supplemental description.</emphasis>
Macropterous female 
<typeStatus box="[711,863,418,444]" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">HOLOTYPE</typeStatus>
: body length 8.20; maximum width 2.10. Head with a pair of convergent, impressed lines and a pair of rounded indentations posteriorly. Ocular setae present. Forewing basal macula concave basally. Pro- and mesoacetabula each with a rounded punctation on mesal surface. Meso- and metasterna centrally with two pairs of small tubercles on intersegmental region. Metasternum with posterior margin convex (
<figureCitation box="[335,419,562,589]" captionStart="FIGURES 14–16" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1734,1758]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1710]" captionTargetId="figure-20@6.[151,1435,181,1710]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 14–16. Paravelia albotrimaculata (Kirkaldy). (14) Dorsal, (15) ventral, and (16) lateral habitus of female holotype (RBINS). Size bar = 1.00 mm and applies only to Figs. 14–15." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810198" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810198/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
). Grasping comb absent from fore tibia. Middle tibia without row of elongate dark-brown trichobothria-like setae on posterior third. Hind tibia straight, not weakly sinuate. Intersegmental region between abdominal sterna II–III with a depression on each side of midline. Abdomen laterally with narrow, longitudinally impressed furrows. Gonocoxae shorter along commissure than exposed portion of proctiger when viewed ventrally (
<figureCitation box="[159,243,706,733]" captionStart="FIGURES 14–16" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1734,1758]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1710]" captionTargetId="figure-20@6.[151,1435,181,1710]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 14–16. Paravelia albotrimaculata (Kirkaldy). (14) Dorsal, (15) ventral, and (16) lateral habitus of female holotype (RBINS). Size bar = 1.00 mm and applies only to Figs. 14–15." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810198" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810198/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
). Lateral margin of gonocoxa without strong angle, evenly curved.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="282" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,417,2028]" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,332,741,767]" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">Discussion.</emphasis>
This species was described from a macropterous female from Valencia, northern 
<collectingCountry box="[1249,1368,742,768]" name="Venezuela" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Hungerford, H. B." pageId="5" pageNumber="282" pagination="23 - 27" refId="ref6708" refString="Hungerford, H. B. (1930 b) Three new Velia from South America. Journal of the Kansas Entomological Society, 3, 23 - 27." type="journal article" year="1930">Hungerford (1930b)</bibRefCitation>
, based on the 
<typeStatus box="[490,588,778,804]" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">holotype</typeStatus>
deposited in RBINS, presented a short redescription of this species, including illustrations of the dorsal habitus of the body and of the hind leg. This same author had considered 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Polhemus" authorityYear="1976" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albotrimaculata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">P. albotrimaculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a member of the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Kirkaldy" baseAuthorityYear="1899" box="[476,621,850,876]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inveruglas">
<emphasis box="[476,621,850,876]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">P. inveruglas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Hungerford, H. B." box="[749,946,850,876]" pageId="5" pageNumber="282" pagination="759 - 761" refId="ref6612" refString="Hungerford, H. B. (1929) A new Velia from Arizona with notes on other species (Hemiptera-Veliidae). Annals of theEntomological Society of America, 22, 759 - 761. https: // doi. org / 10.1093 / aesa / 22.4.759" type="journal article" year="1929">Hungerford 1929</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Polhemus, D. A. &amp; Molano, F. &amp; Morales, I. &amp; Moreira, F. F. F. &amp; Floriano, C. F. B." box="[964,1216,850,876]" pageId="5" pageNumber="282" pagination="295 - 314" refId="ref7021" refString="Polhemus, D. A., Molano, F., Morales, I., Moreira, F. F. F. &amp; Floriano, C. F. B. (2019) Altavelia, a new genus of Neotropical Veliinae (Heteroptera: Gerromorpha: Veliidae), with a key to species and descriptions of four new species from Colombia. Zootaxa, 4585 (2), 295 - 314. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4585.2.4" type="journal article" year="2019">
Polhemus 
<emphasis box="[1081,1136,850,876]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">et al.</emphasis>
(2019)
</bibRefCitation>
proposed the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Polhemus &amp; Moreira" authorityYear="2019" box="[151,252,886,912]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Altavelia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,252,886,912]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">Altavelia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to hold some species previously included in the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Kirkaldy" baseAuthorityYear="1899" box="[815,962,886,912]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inveruglas">
<emphasis box="[815,962,886,912]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">P. inveruglas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group, in addition to others described by them on the occasion. However, they kept 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Polhemus" authorityYear="1976" box="[636,844,922,948]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albotrimaculata">
<emphasis box="[636,844,922,948]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">P. albotrimaculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Breddin" authorityYear="1898" box="[998,1108,922,948]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[998,1108,922,948]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">Paravelia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
due to inconsistency regarding some characteristics, such as the presence of maculae on the forewing (
<figureCitation box="[993,1075,958,984]" captionStart="FIGURES 14–16" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1734,1758]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1710]" captionTargetId="figure-20@6.[151,1435,181,1710]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 14–16. Paravelia albotrimaculata (Kirkaldy). (14) Dorsal, (15) ventral, and (16) lateral habitus of female holotype (RBINS). Size bar = 1.00 mm and applies only to Figs. 14–15." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810198" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810198/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
), which are absent in all species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Polhemus &amp; Moreira" authorityYear="2019" box="[183,284,994,1020]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Altavelia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[183,284,994,1020]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">Altavelia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In the same paper, the authors also mentioned that 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Polhemus" authorityYear="1976" box="[877,1086,994,1020]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albotrimaculata">
<emphasis box="[877,1086,994,1020]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">P. albotrimaculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
would be more closely related to three phytotelma-inhabiting species: 
<taxonomicName authority="Polhemus, 2014" authorityName="Polhemus" authorityYear="2014" box="[604,909,1030,1056]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="loutoni">
<emphasis box="[604,713,1030,1056]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">P. loutoni</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Polhemus, D. A." box="[723,909,1030,1056]" pageId="5" pageNumber="282" pagination="151 - 162" refId="ref6912" refString="Polhemus, D. A. (2014) Two new Peruvian species of Paravelia (Heteroptera: Veliidae) from water-filled bamboo internodes, and distributional notes for other Paravelia species. Tijdschrift voor Entomologie, 157, 151 - 162. https: // doi. org / 10.1163 / 22119434 - 00002043" type="journal article" year="2014">Polhemus, 2014</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Hungerford, 1931)" baseAuthorityName="Hungerford" baseAuthorityYear="1931" box="[923,1260,1030,1056]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="myersi">
<emphasis box="[923,1028,1031,1056]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">P. myersi</emphasis>
(Hungerford, 1931)
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authority="Polhemus, 2014" authorityName="Polhemus" authorityYear="2014" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="reclusa">
<emphasis box="[1325,1436,1030,1056]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">P. reclusa</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Polhemus, D. A." box="[151,336,1066,1092]" pageId="5" pageNumber="282" pagination="151 - 162" refId="ref6912" refString="Polhemus, D. A. (2014) Two new Peruvian species of Paravelia (Heteroptera: Veliidae) from water-filled bamboo internodes, and distributional notes for other Paravelia species. Tijdschrift voor Entomologie, 157, 151 - 162. https: // doi. org / 10.1163 / 22119434 - 00002043" type="journal article" year="2014">Polhemus, 2014</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,417,2028]" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">
After examining the 
<typeStatus box="[431,529,1102,1128]" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Polhemus" authorityYear="1976" box="[566,773,1102,1128]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albotrimaculata">
<emphasis box="[566,773,1102,1128]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">P. albotrimaculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a distinct morphological similarity with 
<taxonomicName box="[1237,1344,1102,1128]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="loutoni">
<emphasis box="[1237,1344,1102,1128]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">P. loutoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
became apparent. Both species share the general color of the body, including the broad, yellow annulation on the base of all femora, and the shape of the forewing maculae (
<figureCitation box="[704,842,1174,1200]" captionStart="FIGURES 14–16" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1734,1758]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1710]" captionTargetId="figure-20@6.[151,1435,181,1710]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 14–16. Paravelia albotrimaculata (Kirkaldy). (14) Dorsal, (15) ventral, and (16) lateral habitus of female holotype (RBINS). Size bar = 1.00 mm and applies only to Figs. 14–15." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810198" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810198/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">Figs. 14–16</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[855,928,1174,1200]" captionStart="FIGURES 17–20" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1884,1908]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,417,1861]" captionTargetId="figure-121@7.[151,1436,417,1861]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 17–20. Paravelia loutoni Polhemus. (17) Dorsal habitus of female paratype (BPBM), (18) dorsal view of head, pronotum, and basal region of forewing, (19) terminal abdominal sterna of female, (20) ventral view of female abdomen. Size bar = 1.00 mm and applies only to Fig. 17." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810200" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810200/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">17–18</figureCitation>
). Furthermore, body sizes are almost coincident, i.e. 
<quantity box="[255,333,1210,1236]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0827999999999998" pageId="5" pageNumber="282" unit="in" value="8.2">8.20 in</quantity>
the female 
<typeStatus box="[465,563,1210,1236]" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Polhemus" authorityYear="1976" box="[600,808,1210,1236]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albotrimaculata">
<emphasis box="[600,808,1210,1236]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">P. albotrimaculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<quantity box="[863,941,1210,1236]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.1082" pageId="5" pageNumber="282" unit="in" value="8.3">8.30 in</quantity>
the female 
<typeStatus box="[1073,1169,1210,1236]" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">paratype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName box="[1207,1313,1210,1236]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="loutoni">
<emphasis box="[1207,1313,1210,1236]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">P. loutoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Polhemus" authorityYear="1976" box="[151,360,1246,1272]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albotrimaculata">
<emphasis box="[151,360,1246,1272]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">P. albotrimaculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName box="[673,781,1246,1272]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="loutoni">
<emphasis box="[673,781,1246,1272]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">P. loutoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the following characteristics: the rounded punctations on the posterior lobe of the pronotum are smaller in size and more densely distributed; the pronotal apex ending at the apical margin of the forewing basal macula; the yellow annulation of the hind femur reaching the first spine of the posterior margin (
<figureCitation box="[391,474,1354,1380]" captionStart="FIGURES 14–16" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1734,1758]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1710]" captionTargetId="figure-20@6.[151,1435,181,1710]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 14–16. Paravelia albotrimaculata (Kirkaldy). (14) Dorsal, (15) ventral, and (16) lateral habitus of female holotype (RBINS). Size bar = 1.00 mm and applies only to Figs. 14–15." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810198" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810198/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
); the intersegmental region between abdominal sterna II–III with a depression on each side of the midline; the gonocoxae shorter along the commissure than the exposed portion of the proctiger when viewed ventrally (
<figureCitation box="[355,439,1426,1453]" captionStart="FIGURES 14–16" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1734,1758]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1710]" captionTargetId="figure-20@6.[151,1435,181,1710]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 14–16. Paravelia albotrimaculata (Kirkaldy). (14) Dorsal, (15) ventral, and (16) lateral habitus of female holotype (RBINS). Size bar = 1.00 mm and applies only to Figs. 14–15." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810198" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810198/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
); and the lateral margin of the gonocoxa without a strong angle, evenly curved; whereas in 
<taxonomicName box="[182,291,1462,1488]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="loutoni">
<emphasis box="[182,291,1462,1488]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">P. loutoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the rounded punctations on the posterior lobe of the pronotum are large and scattered; the pronotal apex extends posteriorly beyond the apical margin of the forewing basal macula (
<figureCitation box="[1060,1143,1498,1524]" captionStart="FIGURES 17–20" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1884,1908]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,417,1861]" captionTargetId="figure-121@7.[151,1436,417,1861]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 17–20. Paravelia loutoni Polhemus. (17) Dorsal habitus of female paratype (BPBM), (18) dorsal view of head, pronotum, and basal region of forewing, (19) terminal abdominal sterna of female, (20) ventral view of female abdomen. Size bar = 1.00 mm and applies only to Fig. 17." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810200" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810200/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
); the yellow annulation of the hind femur does not reach the first spine of the posterior margin (
<figureCitation box="[940,1025,1534,1560]" captionStart="FIGURES 17–20" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1884,1908]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,417,1861]" captionTargetId="figure-121@7.[151,1436,417,1861]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 17–20. Paravelia loutoni Polhemus. (17) Dorsal habitus of female paratype (BPBM), (18) dorsal view of head, pronotum, and basal region of forewing, (19) terminal abdominal sterna of female, (20) ventral view of female abdomen. Size bar = 1.00 mm and applies only to Fig. 17." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810200" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810200/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
); the intersegmental region between abdominal sterna II–III does not have a depression on each side of the midline; the gonocoxae are longer along the commissure than the exposed portion of the proctiger when viewed ventrally (
<figureCitation box="[1020,1103,1606,1632]" captionStart="FIGURES 17–20" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1884,1908]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,417,1861]" captionTargetId="figure-121@7.[151,1436,417,1861]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 17–20. Paravelia loutoni Polhemus. (17) Dorsal habitus of female paratype (BPBM), (18) dorsal view of head, pronotum, and basal region of forewing, (19) terminal abdominal sterna of female, (20) ventral view of female abdomen. Size bar = 1.00 mm and applies only to Fig. 17." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810200" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810200/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">Fig. 19</figureCitation>
); and the lateral margin of the gonocoxa is strongly angled.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,417,2028]" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">
Because 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Polhemus" authorityYear="1976" box="[300,507,1678,1704]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albotrimaculata">
<emphasis box="[300,507,1678,1704]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">P. albotrimaculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described based only on the female 
<typeStatus box="[969,1070,1678,1704]" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">holotype</typeStatus>
, until now its only known specimen, it is not possible to compare male characters between these two species. Field work near the type-locality of 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Polhemus" authorityYear="1976" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albotrimaculata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">P. albotrimaculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<collectingCountry box="[366,481,1750,1776]" name="Venezuela" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
is necessary in order to obtain male specimens and further compare it with 
<taxonomicName box="[1323,1429,1750,1776]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="loutoni">
<emphasis box="[1323,1429,1750,1776]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">P. loutoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="282" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,417,2028]" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,499,1785,1812]" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">Distribution and habitat.</emphasis>
This species is recorded from the State of 
<collectingRegion box="[982,1094,1786,1812]" country="Venezuela" name="Carabobo" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">Carabobo</collectingRegion>
, northern 
<collectingCountry box="[1208,1323,1786,1812]" name="Venezuela" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[1339,1424,1786,1812]" captionStart="FIGURE 30" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1975,1999]" captionTargetBox="[298,1290,982,1951]" captionTargetId="figure-292@10.[298,1290,982,1951]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 30. Distribution records of five species of Paravelia in South America." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810204" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810204/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">Fig. 30</figureCitation>
). Although 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Polhemus" authorityYear="1976" box="[267,477,1822,1848]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albotrimaculata">
<emphasis box="[267,477,1822,1848]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">P. albotrimaculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is morphologically very similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[889,999,1822,1848]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="loutoni">
<emphasis box="[889,999,1822,1848]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">P. loutoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Polhemus" authorityYear="2014" box="[1059,1170,1822,1848]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="reclusa">
<emphasis box="[1059,1170,1822,1848]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">P. reclusa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, both of which inhabit water-filled bamboo internodes, its ecology is currently unknown, so concluding that it also occurs in such habitat is premature.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,417,2028]" box="[199,862,1929,1956]" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,421,1929,1956]" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">Published records.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry box="[428,548,1930,1956]" name="Venezuela" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
: 
<collectingRegion box="[557,666,1930,1956]" country="Venezuela" name="Carabobo" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">Carabobo</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Kirkaldy, G. W." box="[681,849,1930,1956]" pageId="5" pageNumber="282" pagination="505 - 510" refId="ref6738" refString="Kirkaldy, G. W. (1899) Aquatic Rhynchota in the Collection of the Royal Museum of Belgium notes and descriptions. Annales de la Societe Entomologique de Belgique, 43, 505 - 510" type="journal article" year="1899">Kirkaldy 1899</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
